SIMPLE: reluctancy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reluctancy
<hw>Re*luc"tan*cy</hw> <pr>(-t<it>a</it>n-s?)</pr>, }</mhw>
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Reluctant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
state or quality of being reluctant; repugnance; aversion of mind;
unwillingness; -- often followed by an infinitive, or by <xex>to</xex>
and a noun, formerly sometimes by <xex>against</xex>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Tempering the severity of his looks with a <xex>reluctance</xex>
to the action.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn.</b> See <er>Dislike</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had some <qex>reluctance</qex> to obey the summons.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bear witness, Heaven, with what <qex>reluctancy</qex>⟦br⟧
Her helpless innocence I doom to die.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>Magnetic resistance, being equal
to the ratio of magnetomotive force to magnetic flux.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reluctant</ent>⟦br⟧
